3. Scale Up Infrastructure

This infrastructure is designed to scale up the previous setup by improving
availability, performance, and maintainability.

A user accesses the website www.foobar.com through a web browser.
DNS resolves the domain name to the IP address of the load balancer cluster.

Two load balancers (HAProxy) are configured as a cluster.
They share the traffic and provide redundancy.
If one load balancer fails, the other one continues serving requests.

An additional server is added to allow proper separation of components.
Each major component now runs on its own dedicated server.

Web servers are placed on separate servers.
They are responsible for handling HTTP/HTTPS requests,
serving static content, and forwarding dynamic requests.

Application servers are placed on separate servers.
They execute the application logic, process requests,
and communicate with the database.

The database server is isolated on its own server.
It stores and manages persistent data independently
from the web and application servers.

Separating components improves scalability because each layer
can be scaled independently based on its load.
It also improves security and maintainability.

The additional load balancer is added to eliminate a single point of failure
at the load balancer level and increase availability.

This scale-up infrastructure allows the system to handle more traffic,
reduce downtime, and simplify future growth of the application.
